# cURLing For Fun and Profit:

## `/api/register`

### cURL:
```sh
$ curl -X POST https://pageshot.stage.mozaws.net/api/register -H "Content-Type:application/json" -d '{"deviceId":"121", "secret":"124"}'
```

#### Response:
```json
{
  "ok":"User created",
  "sentryPublicDSN":"https://3d2efd7bad9e4e359014cb4e69b8eaec@sentry.prod.mozaws.net/140",
  "abTests":{
    "highlightButtonOnInstall":{
      "value":"control",
      "gaField":"cd3",
      "version":1
    },

      "value":"control",
```

```
}
```

## POST `/api/login`

This will login into an account by sending a `deviceId` and `secret` as JSON and create a session dump to "./sess.json" which we will use for future requests:

### httpie:

```sh
$ http POST https://pageshot.stage.mozaws.net/api/login deviceId="abc" secret="123" --json --session=./sess.json
```

#### Response:


## create

Once you've registered/logged in and created a "./sess.json" session dump file, you can upload a shot by specifying the session file and passing a big-ol-JSON blob (stored in "./fake_shot.json" for better readability/reuseability) to `/data/${deviceId}/${domain}`:

### httpie:

```sh
$ http PUT https://pageshot.stage.mozaws.net/data/bar/test.com --session-read-only=./sess.json --json < fake_shot.json
```

#### Response:

```
$ http PUT https://pageshot.stage.mozaws.net/data/bar/test.com --session-read-only=./sess.json --json < fake_shot.json

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Connection: keep-alive
Content-Length: 167
```
